          "body": "Jeremiah's response to the court is neither a retraction nor a protest. He restates the commission: 'The LORD sent me to prophesy against this house and against this city all the words that you have heard' (26:12). The defense grounds itself entirely in divine authority — he does not appeal to precedent, personal innocence, or political calculation. Remarkably, 26:13 repeats the sermon's actual call verbatim: 'Now therefore amend your ways and your deeds and obey the voice of the LORD your God.' The courtroom becomes the second delivery of the same message. Then Jeremiah does something theologically radical: he surrenders his body to their verdict while refusing to surrender the word (26:14). 'Behold, I am in your hands; do with me as is good and right in your sight.' This is not fatalism but theological precision — his life is disposable, the word is not. The warning about innocent blood (26:15) is simultaneously a legal argument and a pastoral concern: 'if you put me to death, you will bring innocent blood on yourselves.' He cares about the eternal liability of the men trying him."
